@edition "2026.6"

-- D1(xxiii) frontier guardrail. This program is VALID (it type-checks clean — a `_test`,
-- not a `_bad`), but it uses a `try` BLOCK (a scope where `?` collapses to a local Result
-- instead of early-returning the whole function — Design A, SPEC §). eval runs the body and
-- yields a Result, catching a propagated Error into this block's value; the compute spine has
-- no try lowering — `normComp`/`norm` reach the `Try` AST node and refuse it (the `default`
-- arm of `normComp`). The differential harness must report it `unsupported` — a CLEAN refusal
-- at the compiler frontier, never a miscompile.
--
-- This is the backend-slice analogue of a `_bad` twin: a backend slice adds no checker
-- rejection rule, so the guarantee under test is "the compiler refuses what it cannot
-- yet lower, loudly", asserted by the harness rather than by an error count. D1(ii)
-- moved the frontier PAST scalar `match`; D1(iii) PAST tuples; D1(iv) PAST ADT
-- constructors; D1(v) PAST records; D1(vi) PAST lists; D1(vii) PAST closures-as-values;
-- D1(viii) PAST first-class `def` references; D1(ix) PAST first-class BUILTIN references;
-- D1(x) PAST short-circuit `&&`/`||`; D1(xi) PAST non-tail `if` as a value; D1(xii) PAST
-- non-tail `match` as a value; D1(xiii) PAST multi-clause `def`s; D1(xiv) PAST reassignment;
-- D1(xv) PAST atom literals; D1(xvi) PAST duration literals; D1(xvii) PAST `for`
-- comprehensions; D1(xviii) PAST integer ranges; D1(xix) PAST index assignment; D1(xx) PAST
-- the `loop` construct; D1(xxi) PAST type tests; D1(xxii) PAST the propagate operator `e?`;
-- D1(xxiii) PAST the PROP-WITH operator (`e ?: alt`; see compile_propwith_test). The frontier
-- now sits at the `try` block. This file uses one, so it still refuses; when `try` lowers (a
-- later D1 slice, a Result-collecting block), it flips from `unsupported` to a print with no edit.

def parsePos(n: Number): Result(Number, String)
  if n > 0 then Ok(n) else Error("neg")

def addThem(a: Number, b: Number): Result(Number, String)
  try
    let x = parsePos(a)?
    let y = parsePos(b)?
    Ok(x + y)

def main(): Effect [io] ()
  println(addThem(3, 4))
  println(addThem(3, -1))
